  urldate = {2026-03-26},
  abstract = {This chapter provides background information and hands-on processing exercises on the main concepts of Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) remote sensing. After a short introduction on the peculiarities of the SAR image acquisition process, the remainder of this chapter is dedicated to supporting the reader in interpreting the often unfamiliar-looking SAR imagery. It describes how the appearance of a SAR image is influenced by sensor parameters (such as signal polarization and wavelength) as well as environmental factors (such as soil moisture and surface roughness). A comprehensive list of past, current, and planned SAR sensors is included to provide the reader with an overview of available SAR datasets. For each of these sensors, the main imaging properties are described and their most relevant applications listed. An explanation of SAR data types and product levels with their main uses and information on means of data access concludes the narrative part of this chapter and serves as a lead-in to a set of hands-on data processing techniques. These techniques use public domain software tools to walk the reader through some of the most relevant SAR image processing routines, including geocoding and radiometric terrain correction, interferometric SAR processing, and change detection.},
